        {
          "title": {
            "en": "Map the art world"
          },
          "prompt": {
            "en": "[@skill:instagram_post_new:Instagram Post:https://assets-persist.lovart.ai/img/69c4b92dcbc74b44b44187b8cb777e11/60454d7bebccb5c701ea609c4804bd1f891bce3b.svg][@tool:generate_image_gpt_image_2:GPT Image 2 Auto:https://lovart-persist-us.oss-us-east-1.aliyuncs.com/web/icon/chatgpt.svg] Generate a cohesive visual series of high-fidelity infographic-style images forming a unified art-history knowledge system presented as a carousel dataset.

CORE OBJECTIVE: Visually map the most influential and historically significant art styles in human history, and for each style clearly identify the most representative artists, their most iconic artworks, and their historical and cultural influence within the evolution of art, constructing a structured and interconnected “art history intelligence graph” across multiple movements.

CORE TASK (STRICT): For each selected art style, generate one dedicated infographic image centered on that single movement, automatically inferring authoritative art history knowledge including the definition and time period, globally recognized representative artists, museum-level iconic artworks, and lineage relationships with preceding and succeeding movements, while constructing a structured knowledge graph where nodes represent artists, artworks, movements, and optionally institutions such as museums or academies, and connections are clearly labeled relationships such as influenced by, reaction against, student of, museum collection of, or pioneer of, with small visual thumbnails or artwork icons included where appropriate.

VISUAL SYSTEM (GLOBAL CONSISTENCY): All images must use an identical background system consisting of a soft neutral off-white or very light museum-gray gradient with zero variation, no dark themes, and no color mood shifts, maintaining the feeling of a unified museum archive or art history database.

TYPOGRAPHY AND TEXT STABILITY: Use an elegant modern serif or editorial sans-serif hybrid consistent with museum catalog design, ensuring all text is fully readable, properly spaced, and never stretched, warped, or compressed, strictly avoiding distorted typography, perspective-angled text, or improperly scaled labels, while maintaining a consistent hierarchy where the art style name is the largest title, artists are medium-sized, artworks are slightly smaller but highly legible, and metadata is minimal and subtle in gray.

VISUAL STYLE: The system should feel like a high-end museum catalog combined with an art history textbook and Apple-level information design, using a clean grid-based editorial layout, subtle paper or archival texture, soft shadows, restrained elegance, and thin connection lines in sepia, charcoal, or muted blue, resulting in dense yet highly structured academic visualization.

LAYOUT RULES (STRICT CONSISTENCY): All images must share an identical grid system and node encoding logic where art movements are represented as the largest central node or band, artists as circular nodes, artworks as rectangular image cards, institutions as rounded rectangles, and influences as directional arrows, with relationship encoding using solid lines for direct influence, dashed lines for stylistic reaction or reinterpretation, and dotted lines for indirect or historical lineage.

VISUAL HIERARCHY: The composition must maintain a clear hierarchy where the central focus is the art movement, first-degree artists form the closest cluster around it, artworks are directly attached to their corresponding artist nodes, and broader historical context appears as a faded outer layer, balancing radial and hierarchical graph structures for clarity and depth.

CONTENT INTEGRITY (CRITICAL): Use only historically verified and widely accepted art history knowledge, include no fictional artists, artworks, or movements, and restrict selections to canonical styles such as Renaissance, Baroque, Impressionism, Cubism, Surrealism, and Abstract Expressionism, omitting any uncertain attributions and prioritizing museum-level consensus and academic accuracy.

OUTPUT FORMAT: Generate a cohesive carousel-style dataset where each image represents one art style knowledge graph, continuing across multiple major canonical movements in a consistent sequence.

FINAL QUALITY BAR: The result must feel like a museum-grade art history intelligence system with a fully unified visual language, zero stylistic drift, immediate readability combined with deep structured information, and an overall impression of a Bloomberg terminal for art history merged with a MoMA archival system and Apple-level information design."
          },
          "images": [
            "https://assets-persist.lovart.ai/img/ee8e31c4634247fd8bb0700bd061525e/e01c156b54b12b15975f4f026bed82a6031855b5.png",
